Introduction¶

The automotive industry has been rapidly evolving over the years, with advancements in technology and a growing focus on environmental sustainability. As a result, car manufacturers are increasingly under pressure to design vehicles that are energy-efficient and environmentally friendly. In this analysis, we will be working with a car manufacturer known for producing large automobiles, who is struggling with sales and has approached us to help design a more fuel-efficient car. Using data gathering techniques, we will identify which attributes contribute to higher gas mileage and provide insights to the manufacturer on how they can design a more energy-efficient automobile. The ultimate goal of this analysis is to help the manufacturer improve their sales and contribute to a more sustainable future.

This assignment aims to investigate the data cleaning techniques essential for preparing the dataset while preserving its authenticity for the target audience. The dataset will be examined and cleansed to develop a model that can provide meaningful insights to the automobile manufacturer. The model's outcomes will help to design the best model possible for the company. The assignment is structured into three parts, with each section covering several steps necessary for linear regression. In the first section, we will import the dataset and cleanse it to ensure precise results. In the second section, we will apply the linear regression model to the cleansed dataset to identify the attributes that significantly impact car MPG and suggest ways to improve them. The final phase will refine the model using selection procedures to evaluate its effectiveness. Based on the refined model, we will conclude the optimal factor for a fuel-efficient car for the company.

Data Cleaning¶

To construct the model, the primary focus of the assignment is to cleanse the dataset by retaining only necessary data and removing redundant information. The initial step involves importing the CSV formatted dataset into Jupyter notebook using the Pandas library for Python. Following the importation, it is crucial to assess the dataset's format and type, which can be achieved by printing it out and identifying the columns containing data on displacement, cylinders, weight, horsepower, acceleration, and model year. By employing Python's dtypes and shape functions, the characteristics of each column can be determined, and it can be determined that the dataset contains 398 rows and 8 columns of three distinct data types: integers, decimals, and objects. Before using the model, the dataset must be cleansed by ensuring that the correct data type is used, null values are replaced with the mean, mode, or median, and irrelevant columns that may not affect the results are removed.

Checking Null values¶

No significant effect on model accuracy was observed after removing "?" rows, so the data was kept and modified. Data type was changed to integer after replacing "?" values with column mean.

Splitting the Data¶

To construct the model, the dataset was split into two distinct groups. The first group solely contained MPG, which is the dependent variable, while the other group consisted of additional car features, the independent variables. Subsequently, the dataset was partitioned into a train and test set to carry out the regression analysis. The linear regression technique will be utilized to identify the variables that have a greater effect on the car's MPG now that we have a train and test dataset that was separated using an 8:2 ratio.

Modelling¶

The linear regression model was utilized on the car dataset to investigate the various factors that influence car pricing. The dataset comprises several columns that have an effect on MPG, either positively or negatively. US produced and model year are the two most crucial factors, with coefficients of -2.571 and 0.81, respectively. Moreover, the two significant factors that have a negative impact on car pricing are US-made and cylinder, with values of -2.571 and -0.6712, respectively. We utilized the linear regression model to predict car prices, and while some columns have a negative effect on MPG, most do not. We verified the model's accuracy to establish its validity, and it demonstrated a reasonably good accuracy rate of 82.81 percent. The adjusted R-square value is 82.4 percent, while the F-statistics are 213.4, and the log-likelihood is - 826.29. The AIC and BIC values were 1669 and 1699, respectively. To obtain an accurate result, we can optimize the model using multiple selection techniques to improve the model's precision and select the best qualities overall. In the subsequent section of the project, the forward selection strategy was utilized to build an accurate model and features.

¶

To produce a simpler and easily understandable model, stepwise regression is used to select the key variables when running a regression model with a lot of variables, including extra ones. Forward selection is one of two widely used stepwise regression methods. In this approach, a model with no features is initially created, and the features are gradually added in each subsequent forward step based on which feature produces the most improvement in the model. The sequential feature selection technique of the Mixtend library was used to perform forward selection for feature selection in this model.

The forward selection approach involves setting a p-value cutoff and running the regression with all features, and then including the feature with a p-value lower than the threshold. The process is repeated until all necessary features are included. In this case, the threshold was set between 0.02 and 0.05, and the five most important features for improving vehicle performance, specifically MPG, were identified through seven iterations of forward selection: Weight, Model Year, US Made, Displacement, and Cylinders.

   'US Made'),

After selecting the appropriate features based on the threshold value, the accuracy of the model was found to be 81.80 percent, or about 82 percent. This accuracy is slightly lower than the original linear regression model's accuracy of 82.81 percent, but the MSE was incredibly low at 16.4. Forward selection was deemed the most appropriate method for this model because each characteristic may impact the others, and the data are interdependent. Automakers can focus on these five essential features to improve vehicle performance based on the dataset.

Conclusion¶

Based on the data presented in Plot 5 and 6, it appears that there is an inverse correlation between the weight and MPG of the car. As the weight increases, the MPG decreases because the car requires more power, which in turn uses more fuel. A similar trend is observed with "Displacement," which also negatively affects MPG. The number of cylinders also plays a role in this relationship, with higher cylinder counts leading to lower MPG due to increased fuel consumption. Acceleration does not seem to have a significant impact on MPG, but there are some scenarios where higher acceleration correlates with higher MPG.

A fuel-efficient car should ideally have a weight between 1800 and 2600 pounds, four cylinders, and a displacement between 60 and 140 cubic inches, along with adequate horsepower. If these parameters are met, the car's mileage will likely be higher, and the car's year of manufacture and country of origin will not matter.

According to the forward selection model, the five most important parameters for developing a fuel-efficient car are cylinders, displacement, weight, model year, and country of origin. However, manufacturers should also consider other factors such as wheel design, aerodynamics, seating capacity, and other elements that may indirectly impact the car's performance.
